  "local_port": 35194,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What should I do with someone who talks behind my back and is a fake friend?",
  "response": "I'm really sorry you're experiencing this situation. Dealing with someone who talks behind your back and doesn't value your friendship can be hurtful and challenging. Here are some steps you might consider to address this issue:\n\n1. **Reflect on the Friendship**\n   - **Assess the Relationship:** Consider the history of your friendship. Has this behavior been a recent development, or has it been ongoing? Understanding the pattern can help determine the best course of action.\n   - **Evaluate Their Impact:** Think about how this person affects your well-being. True friends should support and uplift you, not bring negativity into your life.\n\n2. **Communicate Openly**\n   - **Choose the Right Time:** Find a private and calm moment to talk to them without distractions.\n   - **Express Your Feelings:** Use \"I\" statements to convey how their actions have made you feel. For example, \"I felt hurt when I heard about the things you said behind my back.\"\n   - **Seek Understanding:** Give them a chance to explain their perspective. There might be misunderstandings that can be resolved through honest conversation.\n\n3. **Set Boundaries**\n   - **Define Acceptable Behavior:** Clearly outline what behaviors you find unacceptable in the friendship.\n   - **Enforce Boundaries:** If the negative behavior continues, it's important to stick to the boundaries you've set to protect your emotional health.\n\n4. **Decide on the Next Steps**\n   - **Distance Yourself:** If the person continues to be untrustworthy or hurtful despite your efforts to communicate, it may be healthiest to create some distance.\n   - **Surround Yourself with Supportive People:** Focus on nurturing relationships with friends and family who respect and support you.\n\n5. **Take Care of Yourself**\n   - **Engage in Self-Care:** Spend time doing activities that make you happy and reduce stress.\n   - **Seek Professional Help:** If you're finding it difficult to cope with the situation, talking to a counselor or therapist can provide valuable support and strategies.\n\n6. **Learn from the Experience**\n   - **Understand Red Flags:** Reflect on any warning signs you might have missed in recognizing their behavior earlier.\n   - **Strengthen Your Boundaries:** Use this experience to set clearer boundaries in future relationships to ensure they align with your values and needs.\n\nRemember, you deserve to have friends who respect you, support you, and contribute positively to your life. It might be painful to let go of a friendship, but prioritizing your well-being is important. Take your time to make the decision that's best for you, and don't hesitate to reach out to trusted individuals or professionals for support during this process.",
